04678nam a22007455i 9780813552941DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011035598  a97808135529417 a10.36019/97808135529412doi  a(DE-B1597)530248  a(OCoLC)812066679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPS169.C57bP65 2012 4aPS169.C57bP65 2012 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.9/3552231 aPoll, Ryan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMain Street and Empire :bThe Fictional Small Town in the Age of Globalization /cRyan Poll. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (238 p.) :b3 photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Literatures Initiative00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Small Town as a Modern Nation Form -- t1. Sacred Islands in Modernity: The Prehistory of the Dominant Small Town -- t2. An Unfinished Revolution: "The Revolt from the Village" Reconsidered -- t3. Mapping the Modern Small Town: A Circular Imaginary -- t4. A New Machine in the Small- Town Garden: Periodizing an Automodernity -- t5. The Formation of a U.S. Fascist Aesthetics; or, Welcome to Main Street -- t6. Staging and Archiving the Nation: Pedagogical Theater, Thornton Wilder's Our Town, and U.S. Imperialism -- t7. "One Happy World": The Postmodern Small Town and the Small- Town Postmodern -- t8. Global Belonging: The Small Town as the World's Home -- tAfterword: The Global Village -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe small town has become a national icon that circulates widely in literature, culture, and politics as an authentic American space and community. Yet there are surprisingly few critical studies that analyze the small town's centrality to the United States' identity and imagination. In Main Street and Empire, Ryan Poll addresses this need, arguing that the small town, as evoked by the image of "Main Street," is not a relic of the past but rather a metaphorical screen upon which America's "everyday" stories and subjects are projected on both a national and global scale. Bringing together a broad selection of texts-from Thornton Wilder's Our Town, Grace Metalious's Peyton Place, and Peter Weir's The Truman Show to the speeches of William McKinley, Ronald Reagan, Sarah Palin, and Barack Obama-Poll examines how the small town is used to imagine and reproduce the nation throughout the twentieth- and into the twenty-first century. He contends that the dominant small town, despite its innocent, nostalgic appearance, is central to the development of the U.S. empire and global capitalism.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCities and towns in literature. 0aCities and townszUnited States. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aLiterature and globalization. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813552941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813552941.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK